 Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carew","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, James Patrick, Kieran.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire): habitational name from any of various minor places in Wales, in particular one near Pembroke with a major castle, named from Welsh <i>caer</i> ‘fort’ + <i>rhiw</i> ‘hill, slope’. The surname was taken to Ireland soon after the Norman invasion of England and was Gaelicized as <b>de Carrún</b>. In the 16th century a family called <i>Carew</i> from Devon played an important part in establishing the Tudor administration in Ireland.","Cornish (Somerset and Devon): from the cognate Cornish word <i>kerrow</i> (plural of <i>ker</i> ‘fort’), which occurs seven times as a placename in Cornwall."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":0,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":9,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":44,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Carew was born about 1215, in Moulsford, Berkshire, England, his father, Nicholas De'Carew Sr, was 31 and his mother, Katherine Courcy, was 26. He married Alice Marshall in 1238, in Pembrokeshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died before 24 March 1278, in Carew, Pembrokeshire, Wales."},"et":{"about 1215–before 24 March 1278":"umbes 1215–enne 24. märtsi 1278","1215–1278":"1215–1278","1215–1271":"1215–1271","1240–1297":"1240–1297","1242–1286":"1242–1286","1244–1297":"1244–1297","1185–1228":"1185–1228","1190–1260":"1190–1260","before 24 March 1278":"enne 24. märtsi 1278","1190":"1190","1242":"1242","1286":"1286","1297":"1297","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1260":"1260","1271":"1271","1228":"1228","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","11 July 1228":"11. juuli 1228","1213":"1213","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","about 1215":"umbes 1215","1244":"1244","9 July 1271":"9. juuli 1271","Carew Castle, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Carew, Pembr